## Reading

ASER assessments are conducted in the household. The type of school in which children are enrolled (government or private) is also recorded.

### Table 4: % Children by grade and reading level in English All children 2016

| Std | Not even capital letters | Capital letters | Small letters | Simple words | Easy sentences | Total |
|-----|--------------------------|-----------------|---------------|--------------|----------------|-------|
| I   | 10.5                     | 10.2            | 35.5          | 28.5         | 15.3           | 100   |
| II  | 6.8                      | 7.5             | 30.2          | 28.1         | 27.4           | 100   |
| III | 3.5                      | 2.1             | 12.5          | 25.8         | 56.1           | 100   |
| IV  | 1.8                      | 1.5             | 6.2           | 15.3         | 75.2           | 100   |
| V   | 0.9                      | 0.5             | 3.8           | 10.2         | 84.6           | 100   |
| VI  | 0.5                      | 0.3             | 2.5           | 8.1          | 88.6           | 100   |
| VII | 0.2                      | 0.4             | 2.1           | 4.5          | 92.8           | 100   |
| VIII| 0.1                      | 0.2             | 1.5           | 3.8          | 94.4           | 100   |

Each row shows the variation in children's reading levels in English within a given grade. For example, among children in Std III, 3.5% cannot even read capital letters, 2.1% can read capital letters but not small letters or higher, 12.5% can read small letters but not words or higher, 25.8% can read words but not sentences, and 56.1% can read sentences. For each grade, the total of these exclusive categories is 100%.

